    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
                <date>August 26<hi rend="sup">th</hi>. Elul 5<hi rend="sup">th</hi>. 5598</date>
            </p>
            <p>Dear Uncle.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><date>Sabbath</date> is just over and being at <persName>Mr
                    Allens</persName><lb/> when <persName>Mrs. E. Moses</persName> &amp; other
                friends are assembled, I have<lb/> resolved to scratch a few lines by way of
                accompaniment<lb/> to the two sermons I send by her. One I deliver'd on<lb/>
                <add>פסח</add> and the Men today and was composed during the past<lb/> week on
                    <date>Tuesday</date>
                <date>Wednesday</date> &amp; <date>Thursday</date>. The are con-<lb/>nected and are
                a continuation of the Election of <placeName>Israel</placeName><lb/> in the printed
                book vol. 2, and I believe the 2<hi rend="sup">nd</hi> &amp; 4th<lb/> thereof. I
                hope they will please you; yet I fear your<lb/> partiality makes you attach value to
                things of mine<lb/> which otherwise may deserve but little commendation.<lb/> As I
                intend probably to continue the subject I would thank<lb/> you to send them back by
                an early opportunity. I intend<lb/> going to <placeName>N. York</placeName> in the
                morning, but if the weather<lb/> remains as intensely hot as it has been today I
                may<lb/> possibly defer my starting.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Please to console <persName>Aunt R</persName> and
                    <persName>Rachel</persName> on the<lb/> death of <persName>Mr. M.
                    Judah</persName>; I know he has not been<lb/> in communication with you for some
                time, still I have<lb/> no doubt his sudden death will cause him to be<lb/>
                regretted by those so nearly connected with th<add>?</add> him.<lb/> May the Lord
                send his consolation to them to preserve</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>them from further affliction.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Let me have a letter from you by <date>Thursday</date> evening when
                I<lb/> intend being back again at this place, God willing. As there<lb/> has been
                but a few Mendaner<add>?</add> at Synagogue during the sum-<lb/>mer I have delivered
                no discourses, as I do not like to speak<lb/> to empty benches. Thinking that today
                many would be there I<lb/> wrote during the week; but the attendance today was bad
                enough<lb/> This is no great encouragement; but I have never waited for<lb/> this
                much, so I am never<add>?</add> much disappointed.</p>
            <p>Wishing you much health happiness</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I remain</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Your obt. nephew</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">
                <persName role="author">Isaac Leeser</persName>
            </p>
            <p><persName>Mrs. Moses</persName> will give you all<lb/> the floating talk if there is
                any, which I doubt.<lb/> My love to all friends.</p>
        </body>
